Munich 1856 : four maps that change your view of the city
An insane institution , where young people are to meet today .
A pit chapel , where work is now being done on the S-Bahn tunnel .
Small gardeners cultivate the former land of farmers .
The oldest official map of Munich reveals exciting stories .
It is annoying when maps are not up to date .
Everybody knows that , because the Auto Navi showed a green meadow instead of a bypass .
The historical maps of the digital Bayern-Atlas , an offer of the Bavarian Geoportals of the State Government , are anything but current - but for this very reason very instructive .
Especially if you compare them with current online maps .
Then it becomes clear how cities and communities in the Munich Mercury distribution area have changed since the 19th century .
The digital Bayern-Atlas is a patchwork carpet that is not immediately recognizable as such .
The large overview map included more detailed maps for cities and towns , so-called original position sheets .
According to the Bayerische Vermessungsverwaltung ( Bayerische Vermessungsverwaltung ) , these were created between 1810 and 1864 and stem from Bavaria 's first survey .
Your client : Napoleon .
The French army leader occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria .
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographic photograph of Bavaria - for military purposes , of course .
Although the French troops finally withdrew with the peace of Lunéville on February 9 , 1801 , it was the current neighbours who created the idea of a nationwide Bayern-map .
Elector Max IV . Joseph drove the project forward , founded the " topographic Bureau " - and with it the Bavarian surveying administration .
The original manuscript for Munich dates back to 1856 and can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek , just like any other .
The comparison of the past and present is most impressive on the example of the state capital .
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together .
An example of this is Untersendling , which still appears relatively isolated in the 1856 map .
Sendling was incorporated as a district of Munich 21 years after the map was drawn up , i.e. in 1877 .
Today , Untersendling is located in the heart of the city .
The houses of Untersendling are concentrated around 1856 along the current Plinganserstrasse , which was only named in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser , a leader of the uprising of the Bavarian peasants against Austria in 1705 .
Where the Westpark is today , you can see nothing but fields - at first glance : when zooming in , a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears : hand-written numbered tracts from the so-called " Uraufnahme , " from which the property tax was derived .
Small plots no longer occupy farmers there - but small gardeners of the " land in sun " plant .
A large green area is emerging north of Untersendling .
The Theresienwiese , the scene of the Oktoberfest since 1810 , was in fact still a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert .
On the other side of the Isar , the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine .
In the original fact sheet , in the area of today 's Au-Haidhausen district , one reads not only the street name " am Gasteig " or " auf der Lüften " - but also in large letters " irren Anstalt . "
Yes , people with delusions were once locked up here on Auerfeldstrasse .
It was there that the Munich-based Kreis-Irrenanstalt " auf der Auer Lüften " was founded in 1858 / 59 .
From 1872 , Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - the psychiatrist brought in connection with the death of King Ludwig II .
" He was progressive for his time and , for example , ended the chains of so-called lunatics .
In addition , he prohibited the staff from using force against the inmates , " says Hermann Wilhelm , head of the Haidhausen museum , who worked with the institution for an exhibition .
At first there was room for 280 patients , later it was extended to 500 .
At some point , this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar in 1905 .
Since 2006 , the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost , one of the largest psychiatric clinics in Germany , has been located there .
On the site of the former Auer institution , young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich .
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training facilities .
To the west lies the football pitch of the TSV München Ost , to the east residential buildings from the 1980s .
In 2015 , the children 's home " Casa Don Bosco " was built , based on the original building of the Irrenanstalt , which was destroyed during bombing raids during the Second World War .
The Marienplatz was listed as " main Square " around 1856 , the Kaufingerstrasse was called " Kaufinger Gasse . "
The Second World War also brought a decisive change in the heart of Munich .
The Allied bombs tore many holes in the city centre in December 1944 .
A large one has remained to this day - at the Marienhof .
The English Institute , small business houses and a mining chapel from the Middle Ages were once located at the Marienhof , where the preparatory work is taking place these days and the groundbreaking ceremony for the second commuter railway line is taking place on 5 April 2017 .
With the slider , the old Munich map can be compared to the aerial view of today - and the hole at the Marienhof can be filled up .
Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
