Now the Trump White House is taking on the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they begin to attack the statues .
Americans value them as much as anyone - hence the carefully orchestrated fall of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad 's Firdos Square in 2003 .
Stephen Miller , one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime , certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with CNN 's Jim Acosta over the president 's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration .
To be fair , Miller did not attack the statue itself .
A horde of boat owners and liberty-imitators would have lynched him if he had done so .
But he attacked its significance , and in particular the significance attributed to it when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903 , 17 years after the monument was completed .
When Miller slammed Acosta : " I don 't want to go into a complete thing about history here , but the Statue of Liberty is ... A symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world .
The poem you 're referring to , which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty . '
Miller is factually correct , but as he put it himself , it 's not really about history .
It 's about the contemporary resonance to the stirring words of Lazarus , the only ones in which a state invites not just any old immigrants , but the poorest of the poor : " your weary , your poor , / your afflicted masses yearning to breathe freely , / the miserable waste of your rich shores . "
There was never a time when the " miserable waste " was better seen on our screens .
Miller was not engaged in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump 's US .
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural dispute : it is , in fact , a conflict over the meaning of America .
Lazarus - and her friends who lobbied for her words to be placed at the base after her death - knew very well that she was doing a highly political act .
The sculpture was intended to show the links between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn classical pictorial representation .
Lazarus changed this meaning : in her poem , the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice .
And she gives herself a very different name : mother of exiles .
Linking the poem to the picture is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism .
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue , the people from the right wing wanted to change it a long time ago .
The great writer Rush Limbaugh , a kind of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump , argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty did not invite anyone , but rather was an early neo-conservative who brought the American flame to the dying world : " lady Liberty is moving forward .
It is to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world .
The torch is not meant to light the road to the United States . "
Rather unusually , Limbaugh came across something here .
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of the point of view of perception .
The great fanciful act of Lazarus was to see her as she was seen by the exhausted , miserable but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships .
It 's literally about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives .
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they must hear .
And , of course , that 's not the perspective Miller and Trump would ever want to acknowledge .
Their torch is not to light the way , but to ignite the hatred that is their only source of power .
