Blocking critics via Facebook : don 't bid for public office if you can 't stomach hoarding voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press .
Americans loved George Washington , but it wasn 't long before newspapers beat him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles .
He sneered at the criticism , sure .
But he has not silenced his critics .
For in 1783 , Washington said , " freedom of speech can be taken away - and , stupid and dumb , we are led to slaughter like sheep . "
Which brings me to Maryland to Governor Larry Hogan , who needs to work to be more like Washington .
Hogan 's staff have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page .
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for that earlier this week .
The governor 's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous , and the online comment was full of a backlash with " nah , and ? . "
" It 's just Facebook , " a lot of people said .
But it 's important .
And it 's especially important when it 's a guy like Hogan .
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly Democratic state who is astonishingly popular .
He has the second-highest approval rating of the nation 's 50 governors .
Hogan is not a reactionary heat head .
He has shown a firm hand in running his state and strict adherence to principles .
He was also very adept at using Facebook as a primary means of connecting with his constituents and playfully debuting his hairless head after chemotherapy on his side .
Therefore , blocking people coming to the governor 's side - which is a public forum designated as official and staffers paid with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous .
In an interview with The Washington Post , Hogan 's spokeswoman , Amelia Chasse , defended the governor 's actions , arguing that blocking the comments was nothing more than a moderation .
But it 's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hate-filled people wielding the whip online .
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan .
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders : a teacher , an entrepreneur and a pastor , not trolls .
They all said their comments were respectful , thoughtful and not profane .
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan 's Catholic faith .
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie , Md . , was not hateful , but she asked about hate crimes .
" I commented politely that I was disappointed that there was no reaction to hate crimes and other breaking news , " she wrote in the commentary section of The Post .
" I don 't appreciate this idea either , when a number of people take a position on the same subject , some people disrespect it as a so-called collective effort rather than being recognised as a large group of concerned citizens . "
What the governor 's aides called a " concentrated spam attack , " others would likely call " advocacy . "
The Facebook era makes it easy to tailor a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment .
It is much cleaner than in the past to have done the same by sending staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or arresting and silencing protesters .
But that is exactly what is happening digitally .
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for slamming Facebook and other social media outlets .
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked by his Twitter feed .
One of the first milestones on the issue fell in Virginia last week .
The chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment , according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria , when she banned a voter from her Facebook page .
And in Kentucky , Governor Matt Bevin ( R ) also received a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter .
It shouldn 't be that hard .
At the time of Washington , the era of the affordable port had a similar effect to the Internet .
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800 , and anonymous letter writers seized his leadership .
And even then , Washington had anonymous trolls .
The people who used pseudonyms such as " Juricola , " " Valerius , " " Belisarius , " and " Portius " all wrote letters to newspapers that made Washington 's decisions .
Petitions critical of his position on the Treaty of Amity , trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office , according to historical documents collected by the Online Papers of the George Washington Project .
But he did not silence them .
Freedom of speech , disagreement and discourses are at the heart of our nation .
And true leadership means accepting that .
