Poverty and Death in Indonesia 's Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner , she doesn 't use a stove .
In fact , it rarely uses a pot .
At her wooden house in Enarotali , the capital of Paniai rule in the restive Indonesian province of Papua , the housewife usually places a sweet potato - known locally as a " nota " - directly in the fireplace .
After half a hour , the charred tuber is removed and swallowed with eager , unwashed hands .
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also carries out her daily work , such as washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp .
A bucket in a homeless room serves as a latrine .
The youngest of her husband 's four wives , she was not assigned fields .
Polygamy is common here .
Of course , working late can be dangerous : most villagers are unemployed , and many drink heavily , and there are soldiers here .
" Nobody dares to walk around the village after 5pm , " she says .
It is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua , a former Dutch colony that was taken in 1969 after a disputed referendum in Indonesia , when only 1,026 elders were to vote through a public hand-wringing vote in front of the occupying forces .
An existing movement that pushed for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government , which controls the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers .
In 2003 , the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua , with the independent part of Papua New Guinea covering the eastern part of the island .
Enarotali is as remote as it is barren , with a 90-minute flight from Jayapura , the provincial capital , to Nabire , followed by a five-hour drive in the morning .
There is no public transport .
The town of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated iron roofs converted into various yellow-brown tones by rust .
Very few Indonesians have made their journey here , let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners .
Before Christian missionaries arrived , Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamee .
There were other changes , too .
" We weren 't used to wearing those clothes , " Degei says , pointing to her vibrant hand-woven turban , dark shirt and bright skirt .
" We used to have only leaves on our bodies . "
Papua is Indonesia 's poorest province , where 28 % of people live below the poverty line and have some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia .
But it is also Indonesia 's gold country .
The world 's largest and most profitable gold mine , Grasberg , owned by Phoenix 's Freeport McMoran , is just 60 miles from Paniai , a highland province the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000 .
In 2015 alone , Freeport mined $ 3.1 billion worth of gold and copper .
In addition , Papua has timber resources worth an estimated $ 78 billion .
These riches , however , are a source of misery for the Papuans , who ensure that Indonesia 's powerful military maintains a stifling presence .
A 2005 investigation in The New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $ 20 million between 1998 and 2004 , including up to $ 150,000 to a single officer .
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden goose and are treated mercilessly .
Activists say more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped , tortured and detained by the Indonesian military since 1969 .
Mass killings in Papua 's tribal highlands in the 1970s became genocide , according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights .
In the region alone , Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year .
" We Will All Lost , " says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane that included reports of previous year 's atrocities , such as unlawful executions and torture - rape and electrocution are particularly popular , according to another report - and the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations .
" It 's difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week , " says Andreas Harsono , Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch .
The screws have intensified as Papua 's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia .
The province 's population of 3.5 million is 83 % Christian , but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java , Borneo , Sumatra and Sulawesi .
Javanese Warung canines sell fried chicken and Gado-Gado , a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce .
Local people are fighting to keep up .
" The migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the local Papua , " explains Abeth You , a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura for work .
" It cost the native Papua - the Mama-Mama [ the women ] of Papua - their market . "
Indonesian President Joko Widodo , popularly known as Jokowi , promised during his 2014 election campaign to address the inequalities and rights abuses in Papua .
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua 's 29 districts - including Paniai - on the way to the presidential palace in Jakarta .
But little has changed in Papua , and today locals feel betrayed .
" Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored , " says You .
In fact , Paniai suffered a low just two months after Jokowi 's inauguration in October .
On December 7 , 2014 , a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas songs in front of a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers broke through the darkness on a motorcycle .
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights .
One of the soldiers took offence at their tone and later returned with four soldiers , according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai .
The soldiers who had been drinking chased and beat the group with their rifle butts , victims and witnesses said .
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children .
One child , 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo , was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma .
A few hours later , the building of the nearby government commission was set on fire and things escalated the next day .
About 1,000 young Papua men , women and children gathered at a soccer field in front of the local police station and the military command center to demand justice .
They wore ceremonial hunting arches and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird song - by Papua 's Mee Pago tribe .
Some protesters began hurling stones at police and military posts .
As the mood heated up , the soldiers were sent a command over an internal radio : " when the masses resist more than three times , they shoot them dead , " according to an official document seen by TIME , which was not released to local media .
Yeremias Kayame , 56 , the head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali , saw the impending danger and called for calm and urged the crowd to return home .
No one was in the mood to listen .
" When I turned around , I was suddenly shot in my left wrist , " he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house .
Kayame still doesn 't know who fired , but says the bullet came from the ranks of soldiers gathered here .
" It was crowded , a lot of shots were fired , " he adds .
Local man Alfius Youw was hit three times , according to his cousin , who witnessed the shooting .
" I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him , " Yohanes , who like many Indonesians has only one name , told TIME in gloomy mood .
" I saw that he was dead ... I kissed him . "
The chief inspector of Papua police , Yotje Mende , told reporters that his officers only wanted to " secure " her station because she was being attacked .
" We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us , " Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015 .
" It 's about life and death . "
Five young protesters were killed and many more injured , according to Human Rights Watch .
News of the killings only came " filtered " to Jakarta the following day .
For three weeks , Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura , expressing sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the historical grievances in Papua .
" I want this case to be resolved immediately so it won 't happen in the future , " he said .
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he was setting up an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve historical human rights abuses .
But the excuses started almost immediately .
" Most of the injuries occurred a long time ago .
Some were in the 90s and early 2000 's .
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations , but there are processes that need to go through , " he said .
Then Wiranto made a withdrawal when he spoke to TIME in Jakarta on June 5 , saying he had no plans to set up a grievance mechanism in Papua .
Instead , " everything is regulated by law , " he said .
Wiranto , whom the U.N. has accused of " crimes against humanity " that claimed more than 1,000 lives in East Timor 's bloody 1999 independence vote , said 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua had already been resolved , including the Paniai incident .
Families of the Paniai victims greeted such claims with grim incredulity .
" I 've been interviewed four times in the last three years , but there 's been no progress whatsoever , " Yohanes says .
" I 'm tired . "
He says that years later he is still living in fear .
" I 'm scared , " he says .
" I 'm afraid of being arrested by the military , I 'm afraid of being shot . "
His brother Yacobus reiterated the view that people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident .
He says he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four of the victims .
" After I buried the bodies , the military searched for me , " he says .
The shootings have not stopped .
On Tuesday , Indonesian police shot at villagers in Paniai 's Deiyai neighborhood .
