Due to its idyllic location and beautiful views of the village , the historic St. Hilarius complex is a popular place to stay .
Visitors to the sixth charity serenade can be enchanted by this powerful place .
The friends and patrons of Tumlingens have made it their concern to save and preserve the oldest building in the town .
Walter Martini emphasizes : " it 's an unique village gem . "
In 1267 , the St. Hilarius Chapel was first mentioned in the Württembergische Urkundenbuch : Count Hermann von Sulz sold " the mountain with the parish church of Tumlingen and the Vogtei " to Magister Eberhard von Horb and his brother Dietrich for 20 Marks of silver .
According to the text of the deed , in addition to the former parish church , there was a stately court on Tumlingen Mountain , to which the church or the right of patronage belonged , and not the other way round .
People also lived there .
As can be seen from the description of the Oberamt Freudenstadt of 1858 , next to the Unterdorf and the Oberdorf , which can still be seen today in the townscape of Tumlingen , the " Berg " was the third , the stately settlement core of the village .
Old maps dating back to around 1600 substantiate this historical fact .
The right of patronage was born out of the early medieval right of the church .
A gentleman , who built a church , equipped it and occupied it with a parish priest , remained the owner of this church and was able to inherit this own church .
Associated with this was the right to appoint a pastor or to propose to the bishop a new pastor .
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower .
The greatest of the two crumbled on Christmas 1673 .
The newly purchased bell sounded for the first time in 1692 , but had to be delivered later in the Second World War in 1942 .
During the 30-year war ( 1616-1648 ) , the window panes were broken and the bell cords stolen .
The roof was leaking .
In 1796 , French troops camped near the church .
They broke out the pulpit and church chairs and used them as firewood .
Remnants of the church threatened to collapse in 1809 .
Until 1869 , the Tumlinger Hilarius cemetery also served as the final resting place for the dead from Hörschweiler .
In 1823 , the cemetery was extended and the Hilarius church was demolished .
Only the church tower was left standing .
On New Year 's Eve 1834 , a storm split the church tower and half collapsed .
In order to prevent an accident , the tower was demolished .
Only the tower yard , which still exists today , was preserved as a witness to the church 's history , which is 750 years old .
Today , Horst Kallenberger and Rolf-Dieter Wasem of the " Schaffigen Pensioners " are in charge of the Hilarius plant in place of Dieter Dockhorn .
On Sunday , 16 July , the friends and supporters of Tumlingens will be hosting the sixth serenade at the old cemetery of St. Hilarius Chapel .
This is designed by the combo of the Kepler Gymnasium Freudenstadt and with speeches by Kurt Kübler and Reinhold Matteis .
Local leader Hartmut Romann speaks the final word .
The program will begin at 4 : 30 p.m.
Admission is from 3.30 p.m.
At the end of the serenade , a drink will take place in front of the cemetery .
" Enjoy a summer evening under the shade of old trees and with the wide view over meadows towards the forest , " the organisers point out the fantastic view .
The serenade takes place only in dry weather .
The organisers hope that many supporters will support the preservation of the historic St. Hilarius facility , which is important for tummies and people with hearing disabilities .
Friends and patrons of Tumlingen are particularly committed to home care , as confirmed by Serenade organiser Walter Martini .
