Moore 's Ford Massacre : activists resurrect racist lynching act as a call for justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove through a group of spectators in rural Monroe , Georgia , and rumbled onto Moore 's Ford Bridge .
Before the car , which had four black passengers and a white driver , could reach the bridge , a group of white men with rifles stepped out to block its path .
The leader of the mob - a middle-aged man in a pinstripe suit - took a long train at his cigar and looked through the windscreen .
Indoors , the inmates hovered in fear .
" We want this n -- -- r Roger ! " The man roared .
" Get him out of the car ! "
Screams tore the silence as a young black man was dragged from the passenger seat .
Luckily , this horrific scene , played on July 22 , is just a reenactment .
But when a noose is thrown around the neck of " Roger , " almost everyone in the audience breathed very real sighs .
Since 2005 , civil rights activists have come back to Moore 's Ford Bridge to emulate the night when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey - were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946 .
No one has ever been charged with the murders .
" It 's really unfathomable that not a single person has been arrested in all these years - even though we see them in our communities , even though we know who they are , " said Tyrone Brooks , who helps organize the reenactment .
'it 's a smear on a story , but it 's a burden on our souls . '
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia state congressman and a lifelong civil rights activist .
For him , the obituary serves as a dramatic call to action and represents an annual reminder to the Monroe community that an injustice has never been corrected .
" We want prosecution , we want ending , we want healing , we want reconciliation , but first we need to get justice , " he said .
" We cannot achieve healing and reconciliation until we get justice . "
A forensic doctor puts a blanket over the body of one of the victims of the Moore-Ford syndrome on 27 July 1946 .
More than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected in the lynching process , according to FBI files obtained by NBC News .
But none have ever been charged .
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades , civil rights activists say the dual motivation for the Lynch actions has always been known throughout the city : politics and sex .
In April 1946 , a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in the summer primary .
At about the same time as the election , according to the FBI , the black farmer Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner , Barnett Hester , during a fight - allegedly because of a woman .
Brooks said the rumor in town was that Hester had slept with Malcom 's wife , Dorothy , and that the baby she was carrying was not from her husband .
On July 25 , 1946 , Loy Harrison , a prominent white landowner , paid $ 600 to free Malcom from prison , according to the FBI .
He was escorted to prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey .
But as they walked away from the prison and approached Moore 's Ford Bridge , a lynch mob surrounded the car .
" As it turns out , it was Harrison who prepared and ordered the killings , " concludes a FBI report .
" It is also evident that there was a plot between state and local law enforcement that not only participated in the killings , removed evidence and covered up the identity of witnesses . "
Brooks puts it even more succinctly .
" It was an electoral rights massacre , " he said .
" They were all killed for sending a message to black people in this community : " if you register and if you vote , that 's going to happen to you here . " "
For nearly a decade , Cassandra Greene has led the annual reenactment of the Moore Ford Bridge Lynch murders .
Their portrayal is vivid , poignant and grounded in a kind of deep racism that many would like to believe no longer exists in America .
It 's hard to watch , and even harder to look away from , but Greene said that 's the point .
" We don 't want to talk about lynching , because then we are confronted with its ugliness in all of us , " she said .
" But I can 't build a relationship with you if you don 't want to listen to me or not want to hear what I 've been through . "
