The rules , which aim to prevent unimpeded spending by European football clubs , will not disrupt Neymar 's world-record transfer from Spain 's Barcelona to France 's Paris-Saint Germain .
Any consequences will still come for Paris Saint-Germain from UEFA , because the governing body that oversees the European game has the power to ban teams from accessing the prestigious Champions League tournament .
Financial fair play rules , created by UEFA in 2011 , mean PSG will eventually have to prove that Neymar 's transfer was funded without major losses .
Barcelona have paid 222 million euros ( $ 262 million ) to buy the Brazilian out of his contract and Neymar will receive a salary that will be several tens of millions of dollars a year .
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar 's move to France .
PSG can certainly make the money easy for Neymar to sign and take him to a galaxy of other stars , given the team 's funding from the energy-rich ruling family of Qatar .
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money on acquiring players , but must counteract with legitimate sources of revenue that allow them the break-even point in their football-related business .
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007 .
The former French player believed clubs who had taken on huge debts in their quest for success were effectively cheating and risking ruin if banks or owners withdrew their support .
In 2011 , FFP shifted from focusing on the clubs " debt to monitoring their losses .
The change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich originally used at Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and then investing heavily to improve the squad and build a global brand - was to become a tougher one .
During the current three-year FFP investment period , which runs until 2018 , clubs can incur losses of 30 million euros .
And although Platini fell out of favor with the presidency in 2015 , his UEFA successor , Aleksander Ceferin , remains committed to discouraging excessive spending .
" Certainly FFP is not dead and we will certainly strengthen the rules for the future , " Andrea Traverso , who is in charge of FFP at UEFA , told The Associated Press last week .
Although PSG paid Neymar 's buy-out clause in a lump sum , it can distribute the amount for accounting over the duration of his contract .
Neymar has signed a five-year contract so that the transfer fee for the next five years of 44.4 million euros can be included in the annual financial statements .
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 hit PSG with the heaviest sanctions , along with Abu Dhabi , which is owned by Manchester City .
PSG were fined 60 million euros ( then $ 82 million ) , which was later reduced to 20 million euros - and it was ordered that team members be limited to 21 players for the 2014 / 15 Champions League season instead of the otherwise normal 25 players .
UEFA is looking for clubs who could try to outwit its financial watchdog by inflating their revenues through companies linked to the owners of a club .
While a Qatar company could sponsor PSG if the value of sponsorship were to exceed standard market rates , UEFA would not allow this to be considered a legitimate income .
That 's exactly what happened in 2014 , when UEFA decided that the value of PSA 's sponsorship was inflated by the Qatar Tourism Authority .
It has been reported that part of the PSG payments to Neymar could come via payments from the organising committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar .
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will become World Cup ambassador and such a manoeuvre could be easy for UEFA regulators to find out .
The sanctions against PSG so far mean that UEFA will be even more attentive to any attempt to circumvent the rules .
UEFA had no preparatory discussions with PSG about Neymar 's transfer , people familiar with the situation said on Thursday .
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity as they were not authorized to discuss the PSG situation .
The latest published reports show that PSG made a profit of more than 10 million euros in 2015 / 16 with a turnover of 542.4 million euros .
The accounts for the last fiscal year have yet to be released .
