NHS ( The National Health Service ) to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be given access to " transformative " HIV prevention treatment from September after a High Court battle over funding for the drug in the NHS .
NHS England announced that pre-sexual pre-exposure prophylaxis ( PrEP ) , which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 percent , will now be delivered by the health service via an initial three-year study for an estimated 10,000 people .
He agreed to fund the process after the Court of Appeal last year upheld a Supreme Court ruling that the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund it .
The move , announced on Thursday , was hailed by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens as a " important new intervention , " while the National Aids Trust ( NAT ) described it as a " defining moment . "
Sexual health clinics in London , Brighton , Manchester , Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to sign up and more clinics will follow in October before being rolled out across England in April 2018 .
Pre-exposure prophylaxis ( PrEP ) is a sequence of HIV preparations taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection .
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in people at risk of infection .
Taking PReP before sexual intercourse means there are just enough drugs in a person 's body to prevent HIV infection .
Such medications can be taken every day or so as early as two hours before sexual intercourse .
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men , transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated .
Clinics identify suitable participants who agree with the study , including men , women , transgenders and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment .
People living in England and registered with a family doctor can also sign up for possible attendance at their local participating sex clinic .
The program will cost £ 10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week after an international competitive procurement .
The study aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is targeted , absorbed and implemented on a large scale .
Stevens said : " this major new intervention should complement and overhaul the wide-ranging and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV .
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity 's greatest health challenges . "
Deborah Gold , chief executive at NAT ( National Aids Trust ) , said : " this is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV .
PReP , when targeted at vulnerable and vulnerable people , offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic .
From September , people at high HIV risk will have access to this NHS funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner , leading to the improvement of many , many lives .
We warmly welcome this announcement . "
Ian Green , chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust , said : " the priority now has to be for the study to be carried out quickly across the country and for no one at risk for HIV to be left behind .
Now that PrEP has been procured , we are well on the way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV . "
Sharon Hodgson , shadow health minister , said : " the start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and delayed implementation by the Government .
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and can end the transmission of this life-changing infection .
