This could possibly raise sea levels , but only to a small extent , writes the British research project on the observation of Antarctica ( Midas ) .
The Larsen C Shelf is the fourth largest ice shelf in Antarctica , covering almost 50,000 square kilometres , according to AWI .
At the transition from the mainland it is up to 700 metres thick , at the front edge to the free ocean around 200 metres .
It breaks down there on a regular basis .
" Although it 's a natural occurrence and we 're not aware of any direct link to climate change , the ice sheet is now coming into a more dangerous position , " said Martin O 'Leary of Britain 's Swansea University .
" This is the longest withdrawal since records began , " he also confirmed .
Among scientists , it is controversial whether the Larsen C Shelf will now grow again or decline in the long term and possibly collapse , said his colleague Adrian Luckman , adding : " our models say it will be less stable . "
But this development will take decades .
Although these researchers do not attribute the collapse of this gigantic iceberg to climate change , a great many ice shelves of the Antarctic Peninsula have disintegrated in recent decades .
This long stretch of Antarctica stretches towards South America .
According to data from the British Antarctic Survey research programme , the ice surface of the Antarctic Peninsula has declined by 28,000 square kilometres since the 1950s .
The rise in temperature has contributed to the decline .
The Antarctic Peninsula has warmed by around three degrees in the past 50 years , making it one of the areas where the temperature is rising most rapidly .
