Dinosaur used camouflage to evade its enemies
At first glance , it looks like a statue , albeit a terrifying one .
Now , researchers have found that the initial findings of a Canadian miner 's incredible rhino were so well preserved that experts have described it as the " Mona Lisa of dinosaurs . "
It was so well preserved that they could even find that its scaly skin was of reddish brown - and they said it had something of a " troubled past . "
The report in the journal Current Biology described him as " the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world . "
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period between 110 million and 112 million years ago .
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has stunned researchers who describe it as " truly remarkable "
According to reports in National Geographic , the armored herbivore is the best preserved fossil of its kind .
It was found by Shawn Funk while he was digging at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta , Canada , on March 21 , 2011 .
He encountered something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock and decided to look more closely .
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology .
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal within the 2,500 pound ( 1,100 kg ) earthen clump .
After all this hard work , the finished result is now ready to be unveiled .
" If you just blink a little with your eyes , you could almost believe it was asleep , " said lead author Caleb Brown , a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum , where the creature can be seen .
" It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs . "
Researchers have found that although this herbivore is covered with an armor and resembles a walking tank , it was likely threatened by meat-eating dinosaurs .
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and used a shielding technique known as counter-shading , which is also used by many modern animals .
This would have allowed it to blend better into its surroundings and evade its enemies , experts say , suggesting it was threatened by larger dinosaurs .
The 110 million-year-old creature from the Nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology .
Researchers have now studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell , one of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly uncovering it .
The astounding preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor across his body .
They discovered the counter shading , a common defence method in the animal kingdom , meaning the top of the creature was darker than its bottom .
Although the countershading is common , the results are surprising , as the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of the animals living today .
It suggests that the dinosaur was chased by enough pressure by meat-eating dinosaurs that evolution favoured concealment of confrontation as a means of survival .
But most contemporary animals that use the countershading - think deer , zebras or shingles - are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey , signaling that this nodosaur was facing a real struggle for survival .
" Strong predator behavior on a massive , heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous period must have been , " brown said .
The chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur 's skin was reddish-brown .
Scientists are continuing to examine the animal for clues about its life , including its preserved intestine , to find out what it ate as its last meal .
They believe the dinosaur , when it died , got into a river and was driven out to sea , where it sank on its back to the seabed .
At the time , Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today , and rivers and oceans probably spread much further inland than they are today .
" This nodosaur is truly remarkable because it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin , but is also preserved in three dimensions and retains the original shape of the animal , " brown said .
" The result is that the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous period .
You don 't need to use much imagination to reconstruct it . If you just look a little with your eyes , you might almost think he 's asleep . "
The Cretaceous period was a time when huge theropods , carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs , passed through the Earth .
Although the king of them , the Tyrannosaurus Rex , lived millions of years after Borealopelta , the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of its fearsome ancestors .
This includes the Acrocanthosaurus , a 38-foot ( 11.5 m ) long , six-ton monster .
The scientists , whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology , believe Borealopelta sank into the sea after death and was mummified in mud .
The creature was found by Shawn Funk while he was digging at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta , Canada , on March 21 , 2011 .
According to the museum , it is the world 's best-preserved armored dinosaur , including skin and armour , and is complete from snout to hip .
The creatures averaged about 18 feet ( 5 meters ) long and weighed as much as 3,000 pounds ( 1,300 kg ) .
It contained two 20-inch long tops that protruded from his shoulders .
The researchers believe the armored herbivore swam through western Canada until a flooded river flooded it into the open sea .
But the dinosaur 's underwater burial preserved its armour in exquisite detail .
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the skin remains still cover hollowed-out armoured plates along the dinosaur
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic , such a level of conservation is as " rare as winning a lottery .
The more I look at it , the more confusing it becomes .
Fossilized remnants of the skin still cover the hollowed-out tank tops that carry the animal 's skull .
His right front foot is at his side , his five fingers are pushed up .
I can count the scales on his sole . "
