Deutsche Bahn : group tests " comfort check-in "
It is a moment that almost everyone has experienced before : not suspecting you are sitting in the train and sleeping .
Or you are immersed in your work and just have a brilliant thought .
And then : pufff .
If the conductor comes and wakes you up softly or rips the passenger out of the middle of the workflow .
Ticket control .
But the interruptions are soon over .
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing the ticket control system .
You simply confirm by mobile phone that you have taken your seat and are devaluing the ticket .
Currently , a test run is underway on two routes .
" If the offer arrives , we will extend it .
It will then be available on many other long-distance routes in Germany at the beginning of next year , " said a railway spokesman .
" Comfort check-in " is the name given by the train to the discounting of tickets without conductors .
In order to be able to use them , however , a number of requirements have to be met : you need a smartphone or a tablet .
And you have to book an online ticket - which most passengers already do .
You also have to buy it via the Deutsche Bahn app , DB Navigator , which is the most convenient way to book your ticket .
And last but not least , you need a seat reservation .
Because the " comfort check-in " works like this : you get on the train , call up your ticket under " my tickets . "
The test customers will then see a button for electronic devaluation .
Train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that passenger X is on the train and has taken the booked seat Y.
If the train attendant arrives at the ticket control at Place Y , he will know that there is a passenger sitting there with an already validated online ticket .
So you can continue to sleep , keep working , keep quiet .
The " check-in " has two advantages : one for the customer , one for the train - which in turn should benefit the passengers .
" If you want to travel relaxed without ticket control by our train attendants , simply check in the DB Navigator yourself .
This allows passengers to personalise their travel time on the train , " says Michael Peterson , marketing director of DB Fernverkehr .
Second plus : " and our employees have more time than they do today to respond to individual customer needs . "
Those who often travel by train know that , in addition to delays and missed trains , ticket checks are one of the biggest annoyances .
Because you often have yourself , but in any case one of the passengers does not have all the documents you need for the devaluation of online tickets .
Either there is no credit card or identity card , or there is no other document to show .
The result is endless discussions between train attendants and passengers , which leads to bad mood in the compartment or large space and delays in checking one 's ticket , and ultimately deprives the conductor of time to deal with other concerns .
Only a small number of test customers can still use the new service .
And only on the ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen connections .
Other train numbers on the same route have not yet been released .
How an activist came to learn the answer to the question : " whose Streets ? "
On 9 August 2014 , Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core .
Just a day after she arrived in New York City , the St. Louis native sat on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone .
She stumbled across a post from someone from high school .
" The police have just killed a 18-year-old child and it is still lying on the street , " it said .
Bewildered , as no one else had posted the information on her feed , she shut down Facebook and opened Twitter .
A user with the handle @ TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline .
The rapper from the St. Louis area was in the process of tweeting live the death of Michael Brown , an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson , Mo .
He posted a picture of Brown 's lifeless body strewn out on the street and would stay there for four hours .
" That 's wild , " Ferrell thought to himself .
But death was nothing new for her and her community .
She dropped her cell phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later that evening .
There were photos of the police tape and people shouting , and of a man claiming to be Brown 's father who carried a sign saying , " Ferguson 's police just killed my unarmed son ! "
She watched a live feed where a policeman stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog .
In another video , she said , another policeman unsecured his rifle and shouted , " I 'm going to kill you ... Animals all . "
" It 's not common , " Ferrell recalled her saying .
'That 's not the kind of murder we 've got used to and can call typical . '
In that moment , I felt shaking .
I was angry and crying . "
She booked a return flight and went home the next day .
After landing at 11pm , she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father 's house and decided the two would head to Ferguson the next morning .
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary , " whose Streets ? , " in cinemas from the age of 11 .
It 's a story of survival and protest , love and loss , strength and resilience , from the point of view of people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers .
When Ferrell went to Ferguson with her daughter , who was wearing a floral dress and a matching crown , the two discussed a conversation they had " about the black experience and the black state " countless times before this morning .
" You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in ? " She recalled what she said .
" We 're going to Ferguson now because the police killed a 18-year-old boy and it wasn 't right .
I couldn 't take them , " Ferrell said later .
" What happened today is a culmination of ... What happened in the past .
She needs to know it and see it and be brought up in it .
It must be well developed , know not only activism and organisation , but also the different layers of the black experience and the black constitution , and what we must do to become free to liberate ourselves .
Even though I 'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn 't personally experience blatant racism , she 's no different from the next black woman 's child .
I feel like I 'm doing her a disservice to keep her away . '
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road , a location opposite the police station that became a camp area as activists waited for the possible non-prosecution of Officer Darren Wilson .
There , Ferrell and her daughter bonded with a local business owner who was making lunch .
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to protesters .
Slowly , a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell .
" My activism changed completely after August 9 , " she said , noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St . Louis was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities .
" I had no experience in organizing .
It 's all come . '
Weeks later , during an evening demonstration , Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan , one of the film 's co-directors .
Folayan said she and her cameraman , Lucas Alvarado-Farrar , just wanted to " document " what happened .
One question came to Ferrell 's mind : " do you want to document or do you try to find a story you can exploit ? "
That skepticism was fueled by myriad cases of people , often whites - in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience .
As Folayan explained in a recent interview , " we had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn 't center their voices and we wanted to do it differently . "
Folayan had already worked with the then co-director Damon Davis , an artist in the field known for his activism around death row inmates .
His involvement brought Ferrell closer to the project , along with six other locals , the team from " whose Streets ? " Followed in the years after Brown 's shooting .
" This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks to us ... We 're talking , " Davis said .
" That was the main thing for me , how these people are portrayed , because that 's how I 'm going to be portrayed . "
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell 's experience - to show that the movement was " not a messiah leader , but a community coming together , " Folayan said - she proved to be the film 's most open participant .
As a result , documents from " whose Streets ? " Reveal surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell 's life as she falls in love and marries her wife .
" I felt like I was naked , " Ferrell said , laughing as she saw the finished product for the first time .
" But I understood that there must be some vulnerability in this work and in the humanisation of black people . "
In addition , Ferrell 's story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement .
Two of the three founders of the movement , who coined the film " BlacklivesMatter " on social media after the 2012 killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin , identify themselves as gay .
" Black , gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement overall , " Ferrell said , " and so we 're constantly fighting on different fronts .
Black , gay women must bear the brunt of everything . "
Folayan agreed , noting that " the movement is really sustained by black women and many black women . "
However , she insists that " this is not an affirmative type of action , " where Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity .
" She was the person who stirred up that energy , " she said .
" It 's not a coincidence , although she 's been on the front line , because with a life at these crosshairs as a black , gay woman , there 's so much at stake .
You can feel their energy through the screen . "
By now , the news cameras in Ferguson have long since disappeared , but the racial ties between the community and the police continue to exist .
Ferrell is on probation for 2 ½ years for blocking a highway at a demonstration .
She describes the sociopolitical atmosphere of the area , which she calls her home : " a mess . "
Still , she 's clinging to a chant and she 's been committed to that memory ever since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago .
" It is our duty to fight for our freedom .
It is our duty to win .
We must love and support each other .
We have nothing to lose - except our chains . "
