A fitting similarity : artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning 's DNA
In the middle of the room at the Fridman Gallery in New York , there are many faces - white , black and brown , almost imperceptibly alike - hanging from cables from the ceiling .
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek tubers and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning .
Manning sent the excerpts from the Fort Leavenworth prison , where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence after she made public classified diplomatic messages through the WikiLeaks website .
The new exhibition , which opened on August 2 , is called A Becoming Resemblance .
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg , whose discipline united her expertise in technology , computer science and the arts , and Manning , a transwoman and trailblazing dissident whose conviction was commuted by Barack Obama when he only had three days left in office .
Dewey-Hagborg has created a sharp , if somewhat intellectual , commentary not only on the formability of DNA data - the many ways they can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also on identity , through the algorithmic analysis of DNA extracted by Manning , from which 30 portraits were created of how someone might look with these genomic data .
Manning , who was born Bradley Edward but has already spoken openly about identifying as a woman since her puberty , was convicted of 20 charges in 2013 , including six violations of the espionage law , computer fraud and theft .
Through prison , her image was suppressed , so much so that there was only one photograph - a grainy , black-and-white selfie in which Manning was visibly uncomfortable sitting in a driver 's seat wearing a platinum blonde wig - with which she was associated .
In 2015 , Dewey-Hagborg just came off the big success of her 2012 project " Stranger Visions . "
In it , the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum , extracting DNA from the waste to create a picture of what these people might look like .
That was when she received an email from a newspaper magazine .
" They did an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison , and they wanted a kind of portrait to accompany this article , " Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition .
And she couldn 't visit at the time and she couldn 't be photographed , so you got in touch with Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to do a DNA portrait .
The artist and her jailed muse became unequal nephews who exchanged several letters over the course of two years .
They even created a comic " suppressed Images , " illustrated by Shoili Kanungo , which foresaw a future in which the president would commute Chelsea 's judgment and she would be able to see the exhibition in person .
That Obama would actually demand Manning 's release after seven brutal years in a Kansas military prison just days after the book was published was a welcome kind of happy coincidence .
There is something deep and strong now , too , in the opening of the exhibition , as Donald Trump waging a war against government whistle-blowers and transgender troops to find new , tweetable ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to address .
