" There was just never consistency and objectivity , " said Errett , who runs the 75-person San Francisco e-Commerce Hair Care company Madison Reed .
She called people from outside for help .
A new breed of human resources start-ups is growing to help companies figure out how their employees feel .
By creating and licensing software that has the specific purpose of measuring employee engagement , it allows companies to conduct surveys , address specific groups and demographic groups , provide employees with anonymity and complaints hotlines , and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass C-Suite executives and approach the board directly .
" You now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for tracking their health , but where 's the Fitbit for your business ? " Said Jim Barnett , co-founder and chief executive of Redwood City start-up Glint , whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement .
Errett said that she gained a better insight into what your employees think and feel during the three years with Glint .
In addition to the Snap-polls and surveys by certain teams , it offers a company heat map that shows at a glance which units have the most complaints and which executives have low approval ratings - so you can drill down on why .
Companies come to realise that you have to stay at the top of the workplace culture so that you don 't become the next Uber to be engulfed in scandal since a former employee posted a blog post describing an environment of harassment where those who spoke were punished .
For start-ups like Glint , this desire for an overview is a lucrative business opportunity .
The global governance , regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $ 118.7 billion in 2020 , according to financial engineering website Let 's Talk Payments .
Denver , Colorado , start-up Convercent , which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior , saw rising interest and activity earlier this year amid the Uber case in disrepute .
Convercent has nearly 600 clients , including Airbnb , Microsoft and Tesla .
Uber recently signed up as a client .
Like Glint , Convercent lets companies send tailored " pulse " surveys , collect confidential responses in real time , and view the heat maps of your problem areas .
It also offers an anonymous SMS hotline that lets employees report bad behavior .
And when the chief executive is involved , complaints go directly to the supervisory board .
" The court of public opinion has caught up with the regulators , " said Patrick Quinlan , the founder and chief executive of Convercent .
If a company is found to be treating its employees badly or behaving unethically , it can experience costly consequences from consumer boycotts , employee turnover and lawsuits , Quinlan said .
Ruby Tuesday , the restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees and over 500 locations , has employed Convercent for more than a year to ensure that employees are aware of policies and procedures and have an easy way to reach their corporate headquarters .
Earlier , if an employee wanted to report a problem , he or she had to find a phone number or email for the company 's headquarters , file a formal complaint and hope it was taken seriously .
It was often an intimidation and uncomfortable experience , said James Vitrano , Ruby Tuesdays general counsel , who said there was no good way to track employees " complaints .
Now that the company is using Convercent , problems previously hidden by executives who sat in offices in cities or states - such as discrimination , harassment or unfair practices - can be identified and addressed more quickly .
" I can get closer to that holistic , 360-degree view into the experience of employment , " said Vitrano , who leads Ruby Tuesday 's Risk Management Group .
" And we protect our shareholders from employment litigation . "
Companies began to take ethics , values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed over ethics violations caused by the Enron scandal , Quinlan said .
But it took until the " social media came to their right " that companies realised you couldn 't stop their dirty laundry going online .
" Before using technology to monitor ethics , people used hope as a strategy , " he said .
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service and charge companies recurring fees for using their products .
It is a business model and an opportunity that has the approval of venture capital investors , who have supported both start-ups .
Convercent received $ 10 million in funding in February from firms including Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital , bringing the total capital to $ 47 million .
Glitter secured $ 10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners , bringing its total financing to $ 60 million .
These investments hardly come as a surprise , given the networked nature of business , culture and venture capital .
There is a growing body of research showing that today 's employees expect more from their jobs than before .
In competitive markets like Silicon Valley , high salaries and interesting projects are just stakes .
Employees want to feel that you are accepted and appreciated and that you are giving your time to a company with a positive mission .
" If people are happy to be in a company , feel that their voices are heard , and that the work you do is worthwhile , then they feel more committed to making this company successful , " said Nina McQueen , vice president of Global Benefits and Employee Experience at LinkedIn , which uses both Convercent and Glint .
Investors get returns when their portfolio companies are doing well , and companies are doing well when employees are engaged and engaged .
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and deployment , it 's no wonder you 'll find support .
The data on employee engagement according to the experts of the workplace culture is important .
But the data is useless if a company 's managers do not take action .
In fact , when a company asks employees for your feedback , they may have an expectation that change is on the way .
And if change doesn 't come quickly enough , or not at all , it can breed disappointments and demotivate employees .
" If you ask for 4,000 suggestions , you have to be ready to have 4,000 conversations , " said Russell Raath , president of consulting at business management firm Kotter International , which has seen companies that have relied too heavily on data collection .
" Because if you don 't follow employees will ask themselves , " have you really heard me ?
Do you care ?
And if you don 't care , why should I ? "
Madison Reed , who now conducts monthly employee surveys , was able to take action on the same day when a problem is reported about Glint , according to Errett .
And after gathering feedback from frustrated employees , thanks to the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication , she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and add a communications training session to address the issues .
At Ruby Tuesday , the company keeps getting new insights about employees , and it hopes that in the long run , this will lead to better retention of workers in an industry known for high turnover .
" If you 're not committed to creating a culture of transparency , you 're going to lose people , " Vitrano said .
" And if you lose people , you lose customers , too .
And if you lose customers , then you will lose business .
