Creating a comic novel : a castle in the history of England
In its recent past , the little Scotney Castle featured in a squeeze music video and was a loophole for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s .
But Scotney has lived through 700 years of turbulent history from his cosy seat in the Bewl River Valley in Kent and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes , a mophaired Yorkshireman with a penchant for historical documents .
" I find it so nice to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years , " he says wistfully .
" What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand . "
" A Castle in England " covers the period from the Middle Ages to the age of Edward and documents the families who lived in Scotney . Each story was illustrated by another emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz , Briony May Smith , William Exley , Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg .
It 's not Rhodes " first book based on an archive : he wrote " Dead Men 's Teeth and Other Stories " in 2014 , a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional .
" I only responded to the thumb print on the side of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins , " he says .
" That 's his thumb print !
And letters always smelled of smoke , because at that time a fire was kindled because of the light .
For someone who lives 300 years later , the smell has an effect as if he were there himself .
Oh , I love archives ! "
For someone so smitten with old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England and lived in a castle for almost four months ( " to be honest : I overrated my welcome a little " ) , this all seems too nice to be true .
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian " new " castle , browsing the archives and studying the castle 's many treasures and curiosities , such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and bottles that had spent centuries digging .
He wandered through the grounds and ruins of the old castle and spoke to landscapers , gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book .
Then , at night , he drank " whiskey and started writing . "
The intimate history of Scotney is relatively unknown as the National Trust only gained full access in 2006 when the last heiress , Elizabeth Hussey , died .
When Rhodes arrived a decade later , employees just started looking after the archive , which he described as " hundreds of years of aristocrats saying " Oh , throw it in the attic . " "
Diaries , letters from the time of the English Empire , maps showing who owned what : " you might think that land conflicts would be boring , " says Rhodes , " but there was a birch around which two families fought .
Guys , let it all go ! "
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve more broadly into English history , including " The Labourer , " which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the peasant uprising of 1381 .
" There is a record of a riot that occurred at the castle in 1380 , in this book called " Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex , " " says Rhodes .
" The peasant uprising began in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start .
Maybe the two are connected ? "
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle 's history - such as " The Priest , " which tells the story of the Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation .
Or " The Smuggler , " depicting 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones ( a discovery made only years later when his coffin was excavated ) .
The Darrells are Rhodes " favourite family of Scotney : " the gentlemen seemed to be pretty crooks , repeatedly making debts and spending money on things they couldn 't afford .
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking guys , with a talent for recruiting heirs . "
After the end of his assignment at the castle , Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences
He completed a two-week stay in the Finnish wilderness for a comic novel about Elämänmäki , the site of an early-20th-century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature .
But Scotney has a special place for him .
" I was sad to go again , " he says .
It was like , " ah , now I have to deal with the damn life again . "
