Around Christmas and Thanksgiving , there were newspapers in the U.S. offering advice on how to deal with the horror of relatives voting for Trump .
We are all supposed to make an effort to burst our filter bubbles .
Less noticed has been the power of Trump to bring families together .
I mention this because my cousin , a left-leaning poet who lives in Chicago and has long dealt with the Republicans in our family , visited me in New York this week .
She reminded me that unity against a common enemy can have a powerful effect .
With Trump in the White House , everyone she knows , including the republican kinship she fought with for decades over politics , is suddenly and strangely on the same page .
Around the dinner table , that 's certainly a good thing , but it strikes me in a wider context that it also carries significant risks .
The left has been strengthened by Trump , but the disfiguring effect of his presidency has the power to push us all to the right .
When we talk about " normalization " and Trump , we are referring to the scary possibility that one day his kittens will not repel us .
There is , however , an even more terrifying long-term scenario , in which Trump " normalizes " right-wing Republicans who suddenly appear as the epitome of reasonableness by comparison with his standards .
I now find myself haunted by an active nostalgia for Mitt Romney 's hilarious version of the madman - the dog on the car roof , the 14 % income tax ( but at least we knew what his tax return looked like ) - both of which , compared to Trump , actually appear to be very mild offenses .
If Trump goes , the next Republican nominee only needs to be mentally healthy to qualify as an immeasurable improvement .
When my cousin was in town , we took our kids to the carousel in Central Park , the largest of the carousels of New York 's parking department , and the best three dollars to spend in the city if you don 't need caffeine .
The horses are enormous , the fiberglass designs on the central cylinder - all the clowns are crunchy and the animals twist to look over their own shoulders full of fear - extremely sinister and the climactic music conveys this in a strange way .
So many clichés disappoint a city : the views of tall buildings are getting old , the skylines are becoming too familiar to offer much excitement , and the reality of the city is not living up to the dream .
