Red meat , dairy products and chocolate could help alleviate IBD ( inflammatory bowel disease )
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare to your digestive system .
But a new study claims just the opposite : a diet rich in button-based proteins and dairy products could ease the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease .
The incurable condition , which affects around 1.3 million in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK , causes stomach cramps and flatulence , recurrent or bloody diarrhoea , weight loss and extreme fatigue .
While sufferers are usually advised to shun meat and dairy products to ease their symptoms , researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan from proteins helps develop immune cells that promote a tolerant intestine .
The lead researcher , Dr. Marco Colonna , explained that immune cells patrol the intestines to ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not penetrate the body .
Cells that are able to trigger inflammation are balanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues .
If the balance tilts too far towards inflammation , it can result in inflammatory bowel disease .
Experiments found that a type of tolerance promoting immune cell occurs in mice that carry a specific bacterium in their intestines .
And the bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to trigger the cells " appearance .
Professor Colonna said : " we have established a link between a type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the intestinal microbiome , and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance .
The more tryptophan the mice had in their food , the more they had from these immune cells . "
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan promotes more tolerant , less inflammatory intestinal milieus , when the same system also affects humans .
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan examined a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found out that a group of study mice had such cells , but another group of the same tribe , housed separately , did not .
They suspected that the difference had to do with the intestinal microbiomes of the mice - the community of bacteria , viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract .
The intestines of the mice were DNA sequenced and six types of bacteria were found , which were present in the mice with the immune cells , but were absent in the mice without them .
Mice were raised in a sterile environment , so they lacked an intestinal microbiome and they did not develop this type of immune cells , and they were given the L. reuteri and the immune cells formed .
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system , the researchers allowed L. reuteri to grow in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the fluid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated by the mice .
The immune cells developed into tolerant cells .
When the active component was purified from the liquid , it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indol-3 lactic acid .
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the lining of the mice , the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent , but when tryptophan levels were halved , the number of cells dropped by half .
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice , and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tracts .
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop the cells in humans as in mice , but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease .
She said : " the development of these cells is probably something we would like to encourage , as these cells control inflammation on the internal surface of the intestines .
Potentially , high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri can lead to an expansion of this population . "
