White House advertising costs cost taxpayers thousands
The White House 's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to the South Lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing last month is costing taxpayers up to $ 24,000 , according to the military , which was left to TIME magazine .
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D , known as Marine One when the president is on board , was the centerpiece of the July 17 event at the White House featuring American construction programs .
President Donald Trump , Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials took a tour of products from all 50 states .
The helicopter , manufactured in Connecticut , was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine , a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi .
The White House military office demanded the presence of the helicopter in a piecemeal order , or FRAGO , barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn , according to records from the Marine Helicopter Squadron One ( HMX-1 ) , the unit responsible for operating the helicopter .
" I just wanted you to be aware of this because it is such an unusual event with high visibility , " the HMX-1 commander wrote to his superior , the deputy naval commander for aviation , on the eve of the event .
The news showed that the helicopter arrived on the South Lawn at around 7am on July 17 for the event at 3pm , and remained until the lawn was cleared between 6pm and 9pm that evening .
The note adds that if the departure from the White House was delayed , a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to the restriction of hours of service .
The original flight crew was on the helicopter during the event , while the unit 's security personnel remained on the ground during the time on the plane .
Records provided to TIME did not clarify whether a second flight crew was ultimately required .
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes .
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event might violate the provision .
" One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that it was not , " the commander wrote .
" Sounds like you 're locked up , " the deputy commander replied .
The " made in America " event was designated as an official event by the White House and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act .
But official events also have political overtones .
At the event , the president gave a push to reform health care reform , which was underway in the Senate , and he touted efforts to curb government regulations .
The use of the aircraft , known as Marine One or Air Force One , for politically advantageous purposes is hardly a new phenomenon .
Presidents are required to use them for travel .
But requesting their use only for a photo op is unusual .
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was providing taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne , Florida , and his Twitter account is full of messages complaining about his predecessor 's use of the presidential plane .
" The White House is excited by the " made In America " show - which showcases products from all 50 states made by American workers using American materials , " said White House deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters .
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights in the Washington area and the South Lawn to drop the U.S. president off at the White House with precise centimetres .
When Trump was in Germany at the G20 summit in early July , HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House .
The flight for the " made in America " event counted in the flight crew 's training needs for the month , an official said .
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for " non-presidential support missions . "
The White House said taxpayers were not taking on the burden for any of the other props presented at the event .
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in issuing the helicopter on the South Lawn .
HMX-1 does not have budget records for presidential flights , and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event .
However , according to U.S. Department of Defense hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year , the VH-3D DoD reimbursement rate is $ 24,380 per hour of flight .
Records of the unit record the plane 's flight time as 30 minutes from the home base of the Marine Corps Air Facility at Quantico in Virginia .
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far below that rate .
" Setting the cost to taxpayers based on the estimates for the reimbursement rates is highly misleading , " Walters said .
" These estimates include personnel , maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual funds . "
According to a 2015 RAND study , DoD reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs , but take into account fuel , maintenance and contract costs .
