Interview : " Domspatzen Report relieves Papal Brother Georg Ratzinger "
The Regensburg Domspatzen report on the cases of abuse relieves the burden of the papal brother Georg Ratzinger .
This is the opinion of author and historian Michael Hesemann .
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen continues to spark debate .
Christian Weisnder , spokesman for the reform movement " we are Church , " said after the publication to the German Press Agency that he expected an apology from the former Bishop of Regensburg and current Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller , as well as from the cathedral master Georg Ratzinger , the 93-year-old brother of the emeritus Pope Benedict XVI .
It would serve the reputation of the Catholic Church very much if Müller and Ratzinger were to express their deep regret at their own omissions or their false assessment of the events at the time .
The Vatican newspaper " Osservatore Romano , " on the other hand , criticized the " double standards " in the reporting of violence among the cathedral patrons .
Regarding the attacks in Regensburg , no one doubts that they are " shameful and shameful acts " that must be punished and prevented in the future , but the " degree of media manipulation " is striking , said author Lucetta Scaraffia , a historian and member of the Italian national bioethics committee .
" The habit of calling the Catholic Church the source of all evils is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to consider it normal , " writes Scaraffia .
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis also commented in an interview with the Bavarian Radio : " people like to go to church and that 's a feast . "
She also pointed out that , in her youth , " beatings were a normal pedagogical means " of coping with naughty children , like I was one . "
It would find it unfair to apply today 's standards to earlier decades , because the world has changed .
In connection with the reports of the abuse cases , the Pope 's brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared .
Author and historian Michael Hesemann , who wrote the book " my Brother the Pope " with Ratzinger ( translated into 12 languages ) , is completely wrong .
" I have to protect Georg Ratzinger , " says Hesemann , " because all this had nothing to do with him , " he assesses the results of the final report .
What exactly does the 440-page report by the lawyer Ulrich Weber , commissioned by the diocese of Regensburg with the investigation , contain ?
A total of 547 Regensburg Cathedral patrons were sexually abused between 1945 and the early 1990s " with high plausibility " by victims of assaults , 67 Cathedral patrons .
The final report says about Georg Ratzinger , who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994 : " to sum up , then , it can be said that in many cases , Cathedral Kapellmeister R. used forms of physical and psychological violence .
Particularly with a high degree of emotionality , the punishment for the pupils could also be more severe .
Nevertheless , unlike many other accused , it is noticeable that many victims appreciated R. " s general humanity and therefore , in many cases , despite violence , even have positive memories with him . "
In an interview , Hesemann explains why , in his opinion , the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen relieves Georg Ratzinger .
Mr Hesemann , the 440-page report on the " incidents of violence against defendants at the Regensburger Domspatzen " gives a contradictory picture of cathedral master Georg Ratzinger .
On the one hand , many students highlight his " humanity . "
On the other hand , he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist , who often became tangible when a cathedral piece failed to produce a top performance .
As his biographer , how do you rate this final report ?
Michael Hesemann : if you take the trouble to read the entire 440 page report from front to back , you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger actually appears in it .
Only eight pages are devoted to him and he is clearly acquitted of any suspicion of complicity or complicity in the terrible cases of sexual abuse .
The violence at the preschool also occurred outside his sphere of influence .
At best , he can be accused of learning of it too late or of not taking the initial indications seriously enough .
The Domspatzengymnasium , on which he worked , was perceived by virtually all respondents as - so literally - " redemption , " " heaven " and " better world . "
So the vast majority of his students , Georg Ratzinger , also gives an excellent testimony , describing him as " warm-hearted , " " popular , " " sincere , " " competent , " and " understanding , " an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly supplied the boys with cakes , biscuits and sweets and was " always surrounded by grapes from children . "
Only a minority complains about his perfectionism and his high emotionality , which sometimes led to outbursts of rage .
Years ago , he himself admitted , deeply regretted and apologised for the fact that he not only cracked chairs and threw the key ring to the floor , but also distributed slaps and pulled all too cheeky boys by the hair or ears .
In order to save his honour , however , it must be said that such methods of education were widespread in the period in question , the 1960s and 1970s , both among parents and teachers .
Do you know such methods of punishment ?
Of course , I think every one of us born before 1968 .
I , too , experienced it in a secular school , a state high school .
Compared to what this report is really about , namely the appalling sexual abuse and violence at preschool , these are , of course , petty .
One wonders whether it is not his notoriety and his role as the brother of Benedict XVI that many of the media rushed to him .
Many people who have never understood him are still working hard on the Bavarian Pope .
But the truth is that the report relieves Georg Ratzinger in every respect !
A great deal has been reported in the media in connection with the report on the subject of abuse at the Regensburger Domspatzen .
Will Georg Ratzinger also be accused in the final report of any involvement or complicity with regard to sexual abuse ?
Michael Hesemann : clearly , no .
Not a single one of the 67 victims of sexual assault claims to have confided in the cathedral chaplain .
Not even the parents were consecrated .
" I never dared to talk to my father or mother about it , " said one of the victims , speaking on behalf of the others , " I was very embarrassed . "
The real problem with the investigation of sexual abuse was , and still is , that most victims remain silent out of shame .
If they did not even entrust themselves to parents and siblings , then certainly not to a choir director , who in a certain way would have been a colleague of the offenders .
How do the pupils of Domspatzen assess Ratzinger 's role in relation to the cases of abuse ?
Michael Hesemann : as one student interviewed put it : " with regard to sexual abuse ... I do not see ... Any case in which he ( Georg Ratzinger ) of all people would have had timely knowledge and could have stopped the respective perpetrator .
I think it is ... Also really absurd to assume that he of all people ... Boys have opened up more forcefully , or more clearly , than to their parents , boarding school leaders , confidence teachers , etc .
That you talk to him about sex ... Unthinkable . "
Thus , the report comes to the very clear conclusion : " it was not possible to confirm that pupils and / or their surroundings had entrusted themselves to him beforehand . "
As far as sexual abuse is concerned , Georg Ratzinger is therefore exempt from any form of complicity .
In this way , he cannot be accused of failing to prevent or bring him to trial .
Therefore , there is no reason to associate his good name with these disgusting crimes , as unfortunately has happened in some cases .
There was a lot of talk in the media about " violent excesses " at the Regensburger Domspatzen .
Former cathedral master Georg Ratzinger is accused of " looking the other way " in the report .
Does he have to live with this accusation ?
Michael Hesemann : that 's the big problem , that in the reporting everything was mixed and mixed into a huge melange of sexual abuse and violence and somewhere in the middle of it , Georg Ratzinger .
But that , in turn , is an abuse of the report .
There is a clean separation : between the preschool and the high school of cathedral patrons , between sexual abuse and violent excesses , as well as , shall we say , other accusations .
In addition , the report deals with incidents from the period since 1945 , including four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not the choir director of the cathedral patrons .
All the terrible pedagogy of beatings , the cases in which boys were literally harassed and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered horribly , all occurred at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen , where truly scandalous conditions must have prevailed .
But Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them , because he only saw the boys when they were already at the Domspatzengymnasium .
On that , as most witnesses point out , the topic of " preschool " was taboo .
One was only happy to have escaped her and enjoyed so much better treatment and , for many , even " paradisiacal " conditions .
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium ?
Michael Hesemann : there was discipline , but no sadistic violence .
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger , for whom the report concludes that " many victims valued the general humanity of R. and therefore , in numerous cases , despite violence , even associate positive memories with him . "
The only thing left is the accusation of having looked the other way .
But despite all the efforts , the report was able to define only two periods in which it was told of preschool conditions .
The first time was in 1970 / 71 , when he was just starting to establish himself and didn 't want to hear about what was going on at a school where he just wasn 't acting and was responsible ( according to the witness ) , and then again around 1993 .
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the conditions ?
Michael Hesemann : no , because back in 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium , which the report even reproduces .
In it , he points out that " caning continues to be practised in the preschool . "
Already in view of the danger of negative press releases , he recommended urgent intervention .
This was , of course , at a time when there was legal clarity , when caning was long prohibited in Bavaria .
Before that , they were in a legal grey area , as we all know .
It was also difficult for him to estimate where those affected may have been exaggerated or dramatised and where the permissible limit had actually been exceeded .
Nor can we say that he has always looked the other way .
That is simply not true .
It was only in 1980 that caning was officially abolished in schools in Bavaria .
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today 's pedagogical standards to the time .
How do you see it ?
Michael Hesemann : we historians are talking about the " pitfall of anachronism , " that is , the danger of assessing the past according to today 's moral standards .
The princess is right .
But , of course , this does not apply to sexual abuse , which was abhorrent at all times , nor to what was breached in preschool in terms of viciousness and violence against innocent children 's souls , which goes far beyond what was common at the time .
It 's all very horrible and I 'm glad it 's finally being worked up .
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger , because all this had nothing to do with him .
His means of disciplining and punishing , that is , slapping and pulling hair and ears , were widespread in the 1970s .
When corporal punishment was then banned , he also adhered strictly to it .
What image of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger give in his conversations with you for the book " my Brother the Pope " ?
Did the subject of caning also come up ?
Michael Hesemann : well , the book is about the life of his brother Joseph , Pope Benedict XVI , tells from his perspective that the cathedral patrons played only a minor role .
Nevertheless , I do not hide the fact that he led a strict regiment there .
But this too must be said : without this perfectionism , without demanding absolute discipline , it would hardly have been possible for him to transform the hitherto rather nationally known Regensburger Domspatzen into a world-class institution , true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition , which went on tour twice in the USA ( 1983 and 1987 ) and Japan ( 1988 and 1991 ) .
With biscuits and sweets alone , you do not turn rebellious boys into great singers and you stand in front of every success , no matter in which field , but always discipline , passion and self-overcoming .
What kind of person did you see Georg Ratzinger talking about her book ?
Michael Hesemann : through the work on the book and beyond , I got to know Georg Ratzinger really well and experienced him again and again as a wonderful , humorous , gracious , deeply believing and hearty person , of whom it is impossible to imagine that he could do anything to a fly .
I regularly hear how many former cathedral patrons still today , 23 years after his retirement , keep regular contact with him , visit him , read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him as a member of their family .
So those who still do not forgive him for once being strict with them are clearly in the minority .
Most cathedral patrons today are grateful to him for enriching their lives and teaching them the world of music .
And that he was always a good , paternal teacher - a strict father , of course , that may be - but also a kind person of respect , whom they still look up to today and whom they almost worship .
And please , let us be clear : all he is accused of are methods of education , which were the order of the day at the time .
We can be glad that we have long since overcome this time .
But it is most unfair to make a man a media scapegoat simply because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother .
The evil intent behind it is all too obvious .
Because the report that has just been published relieves him .
Now , the decency would dictate that a 93-year-old man , who has earned great merits and without whom , outside Bavaria and perhaps still Germany , no one would know the Regensburg cathedral patrons , would finally leave in peace .
